flowRoot.flowPara: Glutamate is an excitatory relative of GABA. It is the most common neurotransmitter in the CNS - as much as half of all neurons in the brain. It is involved in cognitive functions such as learning and memory in the brain. The form of plasticity known as long-term potentiation takes place at glutamatergic synapses in the hippocampus and the neocortex. It is actually toxic to neurons, and an excess will kill them. ALS results from excessive glutamate production.
